{"id":"1001.3624","submitter":"Alessandro Siria","authors":"Alessandro Siria, Serge Huant, Geoffroy Auvert, Fabio Comin, Joel\n  Chevrier","title":"Can nanotechnology experimentally solve the plane-plane challenge","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ins-det","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Non-contact interaction between two parallel flat surfaces is a central\nparadigm in sciences. This situation is the starting point for a wealth of\ndifferent models: the capacitor description in electrostatics, hydrodynamic\nflow, thermal exchange, the Casimir force, direct contact study, third body\nconfinement such as liquids or films of soft condensed matter. The control of\nparallelism is so demanding that no versatile single force machine in this\ngeometry has been proposed so far. Using a combination of nanopositioning based\non inertial motors and microcrystal shaping with Focused Ion Beams (FIB) we\npropose here an experimental set up that should enable one to measure\ninteractions between movable surfaces separated by gaps in the micrometer and\nthe nanometer ranges.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Jan 2010 15:46:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-01-21"}
